04230nam a22006855i 9780231556248DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021048813  a97802315562487 a10.7312/mile205942doi  a(DE-B1597)627190  a(OCoLC)1284921512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBD444 7aLCO0110002bisacsh1 aMiles, Jack, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Friendship in Twilight :bLockdown Conversations on Death and Life /cJack Miles, Mark C. Taylor. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tA Note to Our Readers -- tIntroduction -- tThe Ides of March -- tEaster -- tMemorial Day -- tIndependence Day -- tLabor Day -- tEpiphany -- tWorks Cited0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a time of plague, fundamental questions become immediate and personal. The pandemic, droughts, floods, fire, political violence: the world has been grimly reminded of the proximity and inevitability of death. Jack Miles and Mark C. Taylor—acclaimed public intellectuals and scholars of religion, one a Christian and the other an atheist, close friends for fifty years—have spent their lives grappling with questions of ultimate concern. At the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, locked down at home and facing an uncertain future, Miles and Taylor embarked on an extended conversation about living and dying in an imperiled world.A Friendship in Twilight is their plague journal. In raw and searching letters, written daily from the first lockdowns through the Capitol riot, Miles and Taylor reflect on life during overlapping crises. Amid the menace of the pandemic and the unceasing political turmoil, they debate the lessons that a catastrophic present can teach about the future and how to read, think, live, and face up to death. Confronting the vulnerability of their aging bodies and the frailty of American democracy, the two friends discuss why and how philosophical reflection matters for a wounded world. Their conversations are imbued with an ever-present sense of urgency about the worth of a life, the fragility of existence, and the uncertainty of endings. Seamlessly moving from heartfelt emotion to philosophical speculation, current events to great art and literature, this book is a powerful and moving testament to the precarity of life and to enduring friendship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xMiscellanea. 0aDeathxReligious aspects. 0aDeath-Religious aspects. 0aDeath. 0aFuture life. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Letters.2bisacsh1 aTaylor, Mark C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mile2059440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231556248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231556248/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK